can easily drain water without lifting a heavy bowl, making it a great choice if you have limited mobility. Plus, the built-in strainer catches any food residue from your dishes, preventing drain blockages and ensuring you spend less time \u003ca data-analytics-id=\"inline-link\" href=\"http://idealhome.co.uk/house-manual/cleaning/how-to-clean-a-kitchen-sink-drain\"\u003e\u003cu\u003ecleaning your sink drain\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eBoth washing up bowls also have small legs, so they are effectively standing in your sink, making the disposal of old dish water easier. However, the Aldi washing-up bowl lacks the handles that the Joseph Joseph washing-up bowl sports. This means it is likely to be more difficult to carry, especially if you want to carry water in it.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eBut the most glaring difference between the two is the price point. At £4.99, the Aldi washing up bowl is £30 cheaper than the Joseph Joseph Wash\u0026amp;Drain™ Washing Up Bowl. Because of this, Aldi is a clear winner for affordable price. While I haven’t tried the Aldi washing-up bowl, I have had a good experience with the quality of other Aldi SpecialBuy items, so would expect this buy to follow through on its promises.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv data-hydrate=\"true\" id=\"slice-container-newsletterForm-articleInbodyContent-LEM5yrbyScVrJ4uz6ymQ7W\"\u003e\u003csection\u003e\u003cp\u003eSign up to our newsletter for style and decor inspiration, house makeovers, project advice and more.\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/section\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cfigure data-bordeaux-image-check=\"\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2yJ3uwQbmDTnXtA2Q5SS7f-1920-80.jpg.webp 1920w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2yJ3uwQbmDTnXtA2Q5SS7f-1600-80.jpg.webp 1600w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2yJ3uwQbmDTnXtA2Q5SS7f-1280-80.jpg.webp 1280w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/2yJ3uwQbmDTnXtA